entities and marked by a conflict between those who embraced confessionalism and those who rejected it.This important study will be fascinating reading for students and researchers in early modern English literature and history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aReformationzEngland. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aCatholicism.  aElizabethan poetics.  aElizabethan politics.  aElizabethan regime.  aEnglish Reformation.  aHenrician Government.  aMarian Reformation.  aNorthern Rebellion.  aPilgrimage of Grace.  aProtestantism.  aTudor literature.  aconfessionalization.  acounsel.  acultural poetics.1 aBetteridge, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526130112423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526130112/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles